<HEADLINE>
<P>
DR. JOYCE BROTHERS: SENSE OF HUMOR IS NO MEAN JOKE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. JOYCE BROTHERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DEAR DR. BROTHERS: My 19-year-old son has a wonderful sense of humor, but he 
sometimes uses it to attack his sister and his grandmother. He always claims 
he's only teasing, but his barbs hurt. Whenever I try to talk with him 
seriously about anything, he turns what I'm saying into a joke. Obviously, this 
makes serious conversation difficult. -- B.D. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR B.D.: While it's true that there's usually some hostility in all humor, 
people who use humor to attack are like hit-and-run drivers: They escape by 
claiming they were only kidding and often end up blaming the victim for not 
having a good sense of humor. It's important to put a stop to this pattern and 
to point out to your son that what he's doing is cowardly and cruel. 
</P>
<P>
If he's angry with his sister or his grandmother, then he should discuss the 
problem directly without masking his aggression in humor. Whatever it is that 
disturbs him in these relationships won't be solved until he uses a more 
honest, constructive approach. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR DR. BROTHERS: My 5-year-old son has a terrible fear of dogs. My boyfriend 
wants to get him a puppy for his birthday because he thinks this will get him 
over his fear immediately. I'm not so sure. What's your view? -- R.C.J. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR R.C.J.: The key to overcoming any fear such as this is to do it gradually. 
I believe it would be a mistake to bring a pet into your son's life until he 
feels more secure. This will take time. It would be fine to take him to visit a 
cuddly puppy and see if he'd like to try stroking the dog's fur. If he's 
frightened and doesn't wish to do this, his wishes should be respected. No one 
should make fun of him or force him. It might even be a good idea to start him 
out with a toy puppy, one that's soft and has a coat that feels like fur. This 
might be a totally non-threatening way to introduce him to what a real puppy 
might be like. 
</P>
<P>
I'm wondering if you know the source of your son's fear of dogs. If he was 
attacked or frightened by a dog, encourage him to talk about this experience. 
Let him know that fear is normal but that it's possible to conquer our fears so 
that they don't cripple us or limit our freedom. 
</P>
<P>
You might also take him to a children's zoo where he can see other children 
touching and petting the animals. Again, however, if he doesn't want to join 
them, don't force him. Eventually, if this is handled with sensitivity, he may 
welcome a new puppy, but wait until he's ready. 
</P>
</TEXT>
