<P>
LONG-TERM CARE INSURANCE BACKED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Scared to death" of the costs of nursing home care, most older Americans are 
willing to pay $50 a month for a government insurance program covering 
long-term care, according to a study for the American Assn. of Retired Persons. 
The report should help policy makers trying to craft a solution to the 
long-term care problem, said Horace Deets of the AARP. The fledgling market for 
private long-term care insurance has grown in recent years, with about 1.3 
million policies sold by mid-1989. 
