<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: BIOMEDICAL; 
</P>
<P>
HOSPITAL READIES GROUP INSURANCE FOR SOUTH COUNTY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Leslie Berkman / Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Saddleback Memorial Medical Center is gearing up to market a group-insurance 
plan tailor-made for South Orange County's small-business community. 
</P>
<P>
Judy Simmons, director of public relations for the 215-bed Laguna Hills 
hospital, says she knows of no other instance in which a company has marketed a 
group-insurance plan to such a small geographic area, adding: "We are focusing 
on South Orange County from Irvine through San Clemente." 
</P>
<P>
Through what it calls the Saddleback Health Network, the hospital is offering 
an insurance-benefit package that includes its own facility, two urgent-care 
centers and the services of 200 staff physicians who have agreed to provide 
substantial discounts to plan members. 
</P>
<P>
Simmons said Saddleback Hospital decided to promote insurance for small 
businesses after surveying the Saddleback Valley and finding 15,000 employers, 
85% of whom have fewer than 10 employees. The smaller businesses included 
mom-and-pop restaurants, manufacturers, boutiques, dry cleaners and flower 
shops. 
</P>
<P>
"These small employers often have been excluded from insurance because of the 
expense," Simmons said. 
</P>
<P>
John Johnson, vice president of marketing and sales for United Insurance Co. of 
America, the plan's underwriter, said test marketing has shown that small 
employers in the area want a selection of insurance plans that allow employees 
to share the cost to varying degrees. And some wanted an alternative plan for 
employees who do not live near the Saddleback hospital. 
</P>
<P>
Several plans, including a preferred-provider organization and more traditional 
indemnity insurance, are in final design, Johnson said. He added that the plans 
will be ready for a mass-mailing and telephone-marketing blitz scheduled to 
begin in mid-February. Richard Jacobs, president of Voluntary Hospitals of 
America West, said he may recommend a similar health-care plan to the 
association's 15 other member hospitals in Los Angeles and Orange counties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
